I've been buying SEV, although it takes a while to build a position. They were
selected to provide the control for the Renault Twizy which recently went on
sale.

http://finance.yahoo.com/news/sevcon-hits-automotive-milestone-selection-123000
43.html

Servcon sells controls for electric vehicles of all types and they have
subsidiaries in Europe and Asia. They are HQd in the U.K. but have facilities
in the U.S. as well as in Japan and have made inroads into the Chinese market.
Their sales are recorded in U.S. Dollars, as well as Euros and the British
Pound.

No analyst follows SEV and although it has a small float made more illiquid by
insiders holding more than half the shares, institutional investors hold about
25% of the float. Gabelli made a large purchase in Feb.

Servcon has concentrated its sales efforts on off road and industrial vehicles
in the past, but due to the recession, has been targeting other markets.
Besides the Renault deal, they also have an agreement with Flextronics.

http://finance.yahoo.com/news/sevcon-flextronics-automotive-join-forces-1400006
4.html

They have retained their off road and industrial clients and added new clients
to make up for the reduced sales. Their last q indicated a huge improvement
over the prior year.

I would expect the stock to gain more attention at some point, specially if
Gabelli offers his insight on this stock in Barron's Roundtable.
