Date:4/13/2012 5:06:18 PM
From:E_K_S
OT - Cell Phone shared by the village

Paul - I have made KIVA loans to a few village ladies that provide the use of
their cell phone to their village. It's the only way for the group to afford
the use of a phone w/o having to walk 50 miles to the next village to use a
phone.

The phone allows them to communicate outside their village. Usually they
arrange the sale of their food stuff not consumed. One small farmer sells his
coffee bean crop through a co-op located in the next village. He coordinates
his harvest using the village cell phone based on when the co-op will be
sending their harvest to the local buyer.

When the cell tower infrastructure gets built out around the world and the cost
of use falls in price, this technology (w/ the smartphone) will help leapfrog
the third world into the mainstream. Commerce, education, medical consulting
can now be available to the small village.

I can see where a large developed country approaches a third world village and
offers to build out their cell infrastructure and provide free or a very
subsidized wireless service in exchange for much of their natural resources. It
could be a win/win for everybody if that increases the living standards and the
health of the village.

My long term bet would be owning Siemens AG (SI). They are partners w/ NOK on
their cell tower design and infrastructure division. They usually build to
specification of the local agency and the state agency operates the system
(this is what they are doing in China). SI also has lots of exposure into all
the other infrastructure equipment required to bring these small villages into
a better standard of living.

My SI EK$ value is right around the current price of $94.00/share. The company
yields 3% and has excellent growth prospects all over the world. I plan to
start another tracking position on any sell off into the $80's. My last buys
were in the high $60's and I sold that position starting at lots over $100. I
was out of the stock early by July 2010.

A wild card bet might be to nibble as some shares of NOK, in hopes they spin
off and/or sell their cell tower design infrastructure division to SI. I think
that division alone is worth around $2.00/share last I looked. NOK hit a new
all time low this week of $4.02/share.

EKS
